1
00:00:00,079 --> 00:00:07,010
Conversation generosity is the easiest, simplest, and surest way there is to win a friend.

2
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:14,210
The second benefit of conversation generosity, learning more about other people, is important too.

3
00:00:14,640 --> 00:00:20,129
As we said in Chapter 1, people are what we study in our success lab.

4
00:00:20,319 --> 00:00:25,490
The more we can learn from them, their thought processes, their strong and weak points,

5
00:00:25,680 --> 00:00:33,250
why they do what and as they do, the better equipped we are to influence them effectively in the way that we want.

6
00:00:33,520 --> 00:00:35,089
Let me illustrate.

7
00:00:35,600 --> 00:00:42,210
A large New York advertising agency, like all advertising agencies, specializes, of course,

8
00:00:42,319 --> 00:00:46,930
in telling the public why it should buy the products it advertises.

9
00:00:47,200 --> 00:00:49,810
But this agency does something else, too.

10
00:00:50,079 --> 00:01:00,290
It requires its copywriters to spend one week each year behind counters so they can listen to what the people say about the products they promote.

11
00:01:00,720 --> 00:01:07,010
Listening provides the clues these copywriters need to write better, more effective ads.

12
00:01:07,680 --> 00:01:13,970
Many progressive businesses conduct so-called terminal interviews with employees who are leaving.

13
00:01:14,240 --> 00:01:18,290
The reason is not to sell the employees on staying with the company,

14
00:01:18,319 --> 00:01:20,609
but to find out why he is quitting.

15
00:01:20,880 --> 00:01:25,410
Then the company can bring about improvements in its employee relations.

16
00:01:25,680 --> 00:01:27,490
Listening pays off.

17
00:01:28,480 --> 00:01:31,170
Listening pays off for the salesman, too.

18
00:01:31,440 --> 00:01:36,690
Often people think of a good salesman as a good talker or a fast talker.

19
00:01:37,120 --> 00:01:43,329
Sales managers, however, are not as impressed by a good talker as they are by a good listener,

20
00:01:43,520 --> 00:01:47,329
a fellow who can ask questions and get desired answers.

21
00:01:47,760 --> 00:01:50,210
Don't be a conversation hog.

22
00:01:50,319 --> 00:01:53,329
Listen, win friends, and learn.

23
00:01:53,839 --> 00:02:00,690
Courtesy, practiced in every relationship with another person, is the finest tranquilizer you can use.

24
00:02:01,040 --> 00:02:08,450
No commercial preparation is one-tenth as effective in relaxing you as doing little things for other people.

25
00:02:08,960 --> 00:02:13,329
Thinking right toward people removes frustrations and stress.

26
00:02:13,520 --> 00:02:19,410
When you boil it all down, the big cause of stress is negative feelings toward other people.

27
00:02:19,760 --> 00:02:26,210
So think positive toward people and discover how wonderful, really wonderful, this world is.

28
00:02:27,120 --> 00:02:33,329
The real test for thinking right toward people comes when things don't go exactly the way we want.

29
00:02:33,760 --> 00:02:40,930
How do you think when you're passed up for a promotion or when you fail to win an office in a club you belong to?

30
00:02:41,200 --> 00:02:44,129
or when you're criticized for the job you've done.

31
00:02:44,240 --> 00:02:51,329
Remember this, how you think when you lose determines how long it will be until you win.

32
00:02:51,839 --> 00:02:59,089
The answer for thinking right toward people when things don't go exactly our way comes from Benjamin Fairless,

33
00:02:59,120 --> 00:03:02,210
one of the century's most outstanding persons.

34
00:03:02,560 --> 00:03:10,530
Mr. Fairless, who rose from very modest circumstances to become Chief Executive of the United States Steel Corporation,

35
00:03:10,720 --> 00:03:16,129
said this, quoted in Life magazine, October 15, 1956.

36
00:03:16,640 --> 00:03:19,089
It depends on how you look at things.

37
00:03:19,280 --> 00:03:22,690
For example, I never had a teacher I hated.

38
00:03:23,040 --> 00:03:31,170
Naturally, I was disciplined just like every other pupil, but I always figured it was my fault that the discipline was necessary.

39
00:03:31,440 --> 00:03:34,690
I have also liked every boss I ever had.

40
00:03:34,880 --> 00:03:41,010
I always tried to please him and do more than he expected if I possibly could, nevertheless.

41
00:03:41,760 --> 00:03:48,129
I have had some disappointments, times when I greatly wanted a promotion and somebody else got it.

42
00:03:48,400 --> 00:03:55,650
But I never figured that I was the victim of office politics or prejudice or bad judgment on the boss's part.

43
00:03:56,079 --> 00:04:00,609
Instead of sulking or quitting in a huff, I reasoned things out.

44
00:04:00,880 --> 00:04:04,770
Obviously the other fellow deserved the promotion more than I did.

45
00:04:04,960 --> 00:04:09,010
What could I do to make myself deserving of the next opportunity?

46
00:04:09,280 --> 00:04:16,050
At the same time, I never got angry with myself for losing, and never wasted any time berating myself.

47
00:04:16,640 --> 00:04:20,129
Remember Benjamin Fairless when things go wrong.

48
00:04:20,400 --> 00:04:22,050
Just do two things.

49
00:04:22,400 --> 00:04:29,250
One, ask yourself, what can I do to make myself more deserving of the next opportunity?

50
00:04:29,839 --> 00:04:33,810
Two, don't waste time and energy being discouraged.

51
00:04:33,839 --> 00:04:35,409
Don't berate yourself.

52
00:04:35,759 --> 00:04:37,650
Plan to win next time.

53
00:04:39,759 --> 00:04:42,849
In a capsule, put these principles to work.

54
00:04:43,040 --> 00:04:44,290
1.

55
00:04:44,799 --> 00:04:46,929
Make yourself lighter to lift.

56
00:04:47,040 --> 00:04:48,130
Be likable.

57
00:04:48,399 --> 00:04:51,409
Practice being the kind of person people like.

58
00:04:51,679 --> 00:04:56,530
This wins their support and puts fuel in your success-building program.

59
00:04:56,530 --> 00:04:57,810
2.

60
00:04:58,159 --> 00:05:00,770
Take the initiative in building friendships.

61
00:05:00,879 --> 00:05:04,050
Introduce yourself to others at every opportunity.

62
00:05:04,319 --> 00:05:10,050
Make sure you get the other person's name straight, and make certain he gets your name straight, too.

63
00:05:10,399 --> 00:05:14,690
Drop a personal note to your new friends you want to get to know better.

64
00:05:14,799 --> 00:05:16,210
3.

65
00:05:16,560 --> 00:05:19,489
Accept human differences and limitations.

66
00:05:19,599 --> 00:05:21,889
Don't expect anyone to be perfect.

67
00:05:22,079 --> 00:05:25,489
Remember, the other person has a right to be different.

68
00:05:25,679 --> 00:05:27,650
And don't be a reformer.

69
00:05:27,650 --> 00:05:29,170
4.

70
00:05:29,599 --> 00:05:33,090
Tune in to Channel P, the Good Thoughts Station.

71
00:05:33,279 --> 00:05:38,130
Find qualities to like and admire in a person, not things to dislike.

72
00:05:38,319 --> 00:05:42,130
And don't let others prejudice your thinking about a third person.

73
00:05:42,399 --> 00:05:46,849
Think positive thoughts toward people and get positive results.

74
00:05:46,849 --> 00:05:48,369
5.

75
00:05:48,719 --> 00:05:51,329
Practice conversation generosity.

76
00:05:51,599 --> 00:05:53,409
Be like successful people.

77
00:05:53,599 --> 00:05:55,489
Encourage others to talk.

78
00:05:55,679 --> 00:06:01,489
Let the other person talk to you about his views, his opinions, his accomplishments.

79
00:06:01,489 --> 00:06:03,090
6.

80
00:06:03,359 --> 00:06:05,650
Practice courtesy all the time.

81
00:06:05,919 --> 00:06:07,810
It makes other people feel better.

82
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:09,969
It makes you feel better, too.

83
00:06:10,879 --> 00:06:11,489
7.

84
00:06:11,759 --> 00:06:14,530
Don't blame others when you receive a setback.

85
00:06:14,639 --> 00:06:20,770
Remember, how you think when you lose determines how long it will be until you win.

